<TEXT>
inner mongolia is telling its harddrinking 
populace that getting drunk may soon be illegal 
legislators in the northern china autonomous region are now 
considering regulations that would ban alcoholism the china daily 
reported today 
the official paper said local officials are alarmed by the 
growing social problems caused by alcoholism in an area where fiery 
grain alcohols are a part of all social events and have always 
helped people get through the long bitterly cold winters 
it said every man age 18 years and older consumed an average of 
59 pounds of spirits last year 
seventysix murders 16 percent of the total last year were 
linked to heavy drinking and 24 out of the 126 people sentenced to 
death during the year committed their crimes after excessive 
drinking the paper said 
drunkenness was also blamed for rising traffic accidents and 
divorce 
the report did not say how the legislators planned to define 
alcoholism or what penalties might be imposed for extralegal 
imbibing 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

