<TEXT>
diana simek loves her children but she 
doesnt want louisianas forced heirship laws to determine who 
inherits her property so she and her husband moved across the 
border to texas 
our children will inherit everything after were both gone 
mrs simek said but if i go first i would want my husband to 
have full control over what we built together 
forced heirship is a oneofakind louisiana law that decrees 
that children must inherit a portion of their parents estate in 
the 49 other states people who have the proper will drawn up can 
leave their legacies to anyone or anything 
louisiana is the only state that bases its statutes on the 
napoleonic code which originated in france under its laws an 
only child is entitled to onefourth of the deceased parents 
estate no matter what either parent wants two or more children 
divide half of the estate equally 
such laws were conceived in contrast to primogeniture the 
tradition of giving everything to the eldest son and helped break 
up large land holdings 
state sen sydney nelson has tried for 10 years to repeal forced 
heirship 
it deprives louisiana residents of the freedoms enjoyed by 
citizens of all other states to dispose of their property as they 
choose nelson said other states do have laws protecting 
spouses but ours is the only state that gives the children a right 
to demand a certain percentage of their estate 
but cynthia samuel a tulane university law professor said 
louisiana needs forced heirship more today than it did 30 years ago 
because of divorce and remarriage 
i think our present law tells a very admirable story about us 
it says we respect the moral bond between parent and children that 
lasts a lifetime samuel said its the last act by which the 
parent expresses regard for the people he brought into the world 
mrs simek 50 and her husband leonard 54 lived in 
shreveport for nine years before seeking refuge in harrison county 
texas a 30minute drive from shreveport where they still work 
under texas law if i die he gets everything mrs simek 
said 
their three children ages 29 30 and 31 all live in louisiana 
our taxes are much higher in texas mrs simek said if 
they ever change the law well move back 
nelson said lots of people in the shreveportbossier city area 
in northwestern louisiana have left because of the law especially 
outofstaters who end up there because of barksdale air force base 
many people come to this area to retire after being at 
barksdale nelson said but if youve once enjoyed the freedom 
to leave everything to your wife and children and you find out 
your children can demand a fourth or half of your property people 
are incensed 
people who believe children dont deserve an inheritance did get 
a little more room to maneuver four years ago when the state 
expanded the reasons for which a parent can disinherit a child 
until that time it was reported that only two children had been 
disinherited in 170 years 
now there are 12 sins of the children including failing to 
pay ransom for kidnapped parents refusing to bail them out of 
jail striking or attempting to murder a parent or failing to 
contact the parent for two years 
nelson and others have managed to chip away at the law in other 
ways too 
spouses of the deceased are permitted to have use of community 
property until he or she dies or remarries however a portion of 
separate property continues to be passed along to direct 
descendants immediately if there is no will 
</TEXT>
