<TEXT>
the discovery of more than 1000 documents 
and books that shed new light on early jewish communities in the 
united states might call for a revision of the history of american 
jews 
the new documents show that jews were not concentrated in the 
larger cities of the northeast they settled extensively in the 
deep south much earlier than originally thought and apparently 
viewed the united states as a permanent home not just a refuge 
historians say 
among the other findings are evidence that jews formed 
closeknit settlements throughout the country including the deep 
south as early as the 1820s 
history is only human not divine said nathan m kaganoff 
a jewish scholar who helped uncover the material we now have a 
lot of facts that will lead a lot to be rewritten 
the discoveries come from a private collection of dusty 
prayerbooks playbills rabbinic writings and cookbooks held for 
decades in a wall street safe until purchased for the american 
jewish historical society 
kaganoff learned of the collection earlier this year when he was 
told the items would be auctioned and brought the collection to 
the attention of society benefactors 
benefactors eleanor and morris soble paid an estimated 500000 
for the collection which they bought from art and antiques dealer 
bruce gimelson and donated to the society about a month ago 
kaganoff said the documents show the early jewishamerican 
experience to be a positive one he said the booklets published by 
the many organizations and clubs formed by jews in small towns 
reveal that they embraced their new country 
it looks as if they felt so much at home that they wanted to 
establish their own communities kaganoff said they didnt 
want to return from where they came we thought they were just 
looking for a haven in big cities now we see they went to little 
towns and created institutions that meant they wanted to stay 
in british colonial america the principal jewish communities 
were all in seaports new york philadelphia savannah ga 
charleston sc and newport ri in contemporary america the 
most numerous jewish concentrations are still mostly in seaports 
with the top five in population being new york los angeles 
philadelphia chicago and miami 
the material is being catalogued for display at the society a 
national organization headquartered on the campus of brandeis 
university and home to the worlds largest collection of original 
documents relating to the history of jews in america 
according to kaganoff much has always been known about the more 
recent and greatest influx of jews into the united states the 25 
million eastern european jews who came here between 1881 and 1914 
but the new collection provides a key to the earliest 
jewishamerican history dating from the time the first 23 jews 
arrived in the united states by boat from amsterdam in 1654 and 
extending to 1850 when the number of jews had grown to 50000 
among the most important findings in the collection 
philadelphia not new york was probably the first american city to 
develop a major jewish community though the topic has been debated 
by scholars for generations evidence from the collection points to 
philadelphia kaganoff said 
one such piece of evidence is a rabbinic prayer book ethics 
of the fathers published in 1858 in philadelphia until now a 
rabbinic prayer book published in 1860 in new york was believed to 
be the oldest in the united states 
new york was more like a marketplace said kaganoff there 
were a lot of people but not as much of an organized community 
philadelphia emerged as an organized community and a cultural place 
earlier 
</TEXT>
