by the communist party central committees academy of social 
sciences that was the same day the congress broke into an angry 
debate over the selection of members of the 542 members of the 
supreme soviet standing legislature 
an outnumbered group of reformers complained that regional 
officials had stacked the lists of candidates with legislators who 
would preserve the status quo 
the pollsters said the balance of power in the session was held 
by a moderate group of about 40 percent to 55 percent of the 
deputies 
their report also identified a group with more radical 
expectations and lesser satisfaction consisting of about 25 
percent to 30 percent of those polled and on the other side a 
group with more cautious approaches exhibiting a greater degree 
of satisfaction consisting of about 15 percent to 20 percent of 
the members 
the deputies said they could have the greatest effect in making 
soviet society more open and democratic sixty percent responded 
they could significantly improve openness and freedom of speech 
and another 29 percent said they were capable of making a less 
noticeable improvement 
the report said 74 percent did not regard the opening of soviet 
society as irreversible or considered the changes so far as only 
halfmeasures 
the proceedings of the body ranging from longwinded discussion 
of parliamentary procedure to angry debate and pointed 
interrogation of the kremlin leadership have been televised live 
the figures also indicated that 55 percent found their 
expectations of the congress more or less fulfilled by its first 
days but an almost equal number 54 percent were dissatisfied 
with the handling of procedural questions twentyseven percent 
were most upset about the behavior of other deputies and 26 
percent were most upset by a lack of organization 
a poll of 1832 citizens by the soviet academy of sciences in 
six cities on friday indicated a vast majority of those polled were 
following the congress carefully in broadcasts from moscow and 
generally approved of what they saw that poll was published monday 
by the government newspaper izvestia 
