<TEXT>
white men give and get the majority of transplant 
organs in the united states a disparity that many experts fear 
could thwart efforts to boost organ donation especially among 
minorities 
the bottom line is that there is a racial difference and the 
gap isnt closing said dr paul eggers chief of the federal 
health care financing administrations program evaluation branch in 
the office of research 
transplant doctors will be looking at ways to provide greater 
access to the costly surgery at their annual meeting this week in 
chicago they also will be discussing ways to get more americans 
across the board to donate loved ones organs 
anybody can get on the waiting list but they have to get to 
the transplant center said dr barry levin president of the 
american society of transplant physicians they themselves have 
to want to be transplanted physicians have to refer them 
thats precisely the problem for many women blacks and other 
minorities and lowerincome individuals according to arthur 
caplan director of the center for biomedical ethics at the 
university of minnesota 
if americans dont all have an equal chance at access to a 
primary care doctor forget about a transplant surgeon caplan 
said 
statistics just released by the virginiabased united network 
for organ sharing which administers the national transplant 
network and scientific registry show 832 percent of the 4083 
braindead victims whose organs were donated in 1988 were white 
about 86 percent were black and 59 percent were hispanic well 
below their population share 
on the opposite end whites received 889 percent of hearts 
transplanted last year 859 percent of livers 71 percent of 
kidneys and 976 percent of pancreases 
sixtytwo percent of the 1988 donors were male men also 
dominated on the receiving side getting 792 percent of hearts 
transplanted last year 606 percent of kidneys and 564 percent of 
pancreases liver transplant recipients were almost evenly divided 
between males and females however 
the group excluded from its calculations recipients whose race 
or sex were not reported 
while such lopsidedness does not prove bias exists because for 
example men and women have different rates of some types of 
diseases it certainlysuggests it and that alone poses a grave 
threat to organ donation according to caplan 
the fact that blacks received 217 percent of the kidneys 
transplanted in 1988 is particularly worrisome experts say since 
blacks are four times as likely as whites to suffer kidney failure 
thats due in large part to blacks proclivity toward high blood 
pressure 
onethird of the 107000 americans on dialysis are black and 
onethird of the nearly 15000 people awaiting kidney transplants 
in the united states are black said dr william vaughn the 
networks director of technical services 
both dialysis and kidney transplantation are covered under the 
federal medicare program regardless of the persons age 
a study by dr philip held researcher at the urban institute in 
washington found wealthy white men were likelier to get a new 
kidney from 1981 to 1986 than poor white men the same held true 
for black men the higher the income the likelier a transplant 
i think that if there were outcomes that werent expected 
they were ones of ignorance and not evil intent held said 
experts insist the present selection system is sex and 
colorblind the nations more than 240 transplant centers have been 
required since oct 1 1987 to use standardized scoring for 
allocating organs judging each patient on such things as severity 
and length of illness and blood and tissue type 
the emphasis on tissue matching for kidneys is hotly contested 
among transplant specialists proponents say the practice improves 
the patients chances while critics contend the gains are not 
great enough to warrant having organs lie around and deteriorate 
until a close match is found opponents also contend 
tissuematching discriminates against blacks because a minority of 
blacks have tissuematching problems that make them face a longer 
wait for kidneys 
those kinds of odds dont make it any easier convincing blacks 
to pursue transplants according to howard universitys dr clive 
o callender one of the nations few black transplant surgeons 
the black patient often is not comfortable with 
transplantation for the same reasons blacks are disinclined to 
donate organs he said 
those reasons according to callender include religious 
beliefs lack of transplant awareness and distrust of the 
whitedominated medical community 
another factor he says is that some blacks want their 
relatives organs to go to other blacks a request that like any 
other cannot be assured 
