the uns world food program said monday it needs 
417000 more tons of food to meet emergencies in 1989 and the 
shortage might affect deliveries to refugees 
unless additional resources are forthcoming the program may 
be forced to stop responding to all but the most vital needs 
executive director james ingram said in a report to the 
organizations governing council 
edouard saouma directorgeneral of the un food and 
agriculture organization said the way food aid programs are 
conducted should be reviewed 
he said using cash rather than commodities in some cases would 
allow the purchase of food on local markets 
speaking to the world food programs committee on food aid 
policies and programs saouma said developing countries wanted the 
appraisal partly because new technology and reforms in agricultural 
policy have created the possibility of using locally produced 
staples in aid programs instead of imports 
ingram said in his report the shortage of emergency supplies 
could lead to a disruption in deliveries to refugees and an 
inability to meet unexpected disasters 
he said the shortage included 142000 tons needed for afghan 
refugees in pakistan and iran and 182000 tons for victims drought 
and crop failures in africa 
