<TEXT>
the audience at american ballet theaters 
performance monday was treated to the local premiere of dancer 
clark tippets prettily formal rigaudon 
the title means a lively dance done with a jumping step 
popular in the 17th and 18th centuries 
tippet used 20th century music benjamin brittens 20minute 
simple symphony for strings for his fourth ballet created for 
the company 
rigaudon begins with seven couples dancing in a sprightly 
but courtly manner when the group dwindles to three couples then 
two men and a woman the two men dance together away from the woman 
and she coyly dances to catch up 
in the second movement which britten called playful 
pizzicato tippet is inventive and amusing again he has two men 
and a woman on stage one man kneels the other jumps across him 
putting a foot lightly down on his shoulder 
as the men john gardner and robert wallace show off dance 
steps for each other deirdre carberry exits unnoticed they do 
notice something besides themselves to the amusement of the 
audience when they are suddenly circled by three women 
two threesomes dance the third movement which britten called 
sentimental saraband two men lift a ballerina in various 
elegant postures the other threesome joins hands and dances 
briskly into a variety of triangles and ways for one to peer 
through a window of entwined arms 
all dancers took part in the brittens first movement 
boisterous bourree and again in the brief frolicsome 
finale charles barker conducted rigaudon had its premiere 
in february in miami beach it was underwritten in part by the 
miami premiere society and the equitable foundation it also 
received commissioning funds from the new york state council on the 
arts 
the evening continued with duets choreographed by merce 
cunningham the garden of villandry new to the company this 
season and gaite parisienne the hit of a season ago 
