<TEXT>
a majority of us manufacturers that responded to 
a recent survey plan to expand operations in europe despite initial 
fears they would face discrimination in the unified european market 
slated for 1992 
an overwhelming majority of chief executive officers surveyed 
welcomed the freer market with 84 percent predicting the 
initiative would provide an opportunity to expand their sales and 
operations in europe 
the bank of bostons economics department conducted the study 
for the scottish development agency surveying about 10000 
manufacturing executives in four us regions new england the 
midatlantic states the great lakes region and the southeast 
of the 1234 companies that responded to the survey 57 percent 
already have operations in europe and 91 percent plan to implement 
new corporate strategies before the end of 1990 in anticipation of 
the unified european market 
the 12 nations of the european economic community also known as 
the common market plan to dismantle trade barriers and form a 
single europeanwide market by 1992 
of the us companies polled with no presence in europe 58 
percent planned to enter the market through new subsidiaries sales 
representative offices or joint ventures with european companies 
robert crawford the north american director of the glasgow 
scotlandbased trade association told manufacturers at a seminar 
last week that they must start acting rather than thinking about 
1992 or you will fall further behind 
your strategies related to 1992 must include serious 
consideration of locating in europe and establishing a base if you 
are to gain market share and remain globally competitive he said 
the report said that more than half of us companies with 
operations in europe have their main base in great britain and 
many companies planning to open operations in europe favored 
beginning in england 
the report said a small number of us companies antcipated 
problems with the new european market such as intensified 
competition from newly merged european companies and possible new 
restrictive laws 
but most of those polled said they would welcome 1992 among the 
things looked forward to included fewer import barriers the 
development of uniform product standards and common regulations 
and less bureaucratic interference in commercial affairs 
</TEXT>
